						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">"Screwed up" or just different? Are they more "screwed up" than, say, the GNOME system menus?</div><br />Yes. I find GNOME menus to be well organized enough and user friendly even for someone very used to Windows.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'd recommend making the switch when you buy a new PC, just as you're doing. I'd recommend against upgrading an existing PC to a new major version of Windows at least until it hits service pack 2.</div><br />You got a good point here. When you have to install anyway, if you instal a recent OS it'll take much longer before you'll have to upgrate it for whathever reason.<br /><br />With the IBM-PC standards it's a bad idea to have sofware and hardware not from the same generation -&gt; new software will run too slowly and buggy on old hardware, and new hardware won't be recognized and be used fully by old software. That might not be a good thing, but heh we can't do much about that.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I found the change a bit drastic as well -- but it sounds as if you haven't used Vista</div><br />I haven't ever used Vista, Milenium and anything older than 3.1, because of their non-popularity. I've seen everything else I guess (not counting the server stuff).<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Since you just bought a new laptop, is it possible your distributor illegitimately sold you a copy of W7 OEM? OEMs have their release, yep, but the official retail release is not available for purchase.</div><br />I can't tell you exactly which version it is because the "System" icon that used to always be on the topleft of the desktop since 95 isn't here, and I can't check it's properties. But I got it in a legal way, as a student with the MSDN alliance. This is a great thing, too many stuends ingore it when they can save money or trouble that way.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> <br />One thing I think is a big mistake however is that there is NO upgrade path from Windows XP to 7 even though brand new PC's are still sold with XP, and many were bought with XP because people didn't like Vista.</div><br />It's not hard to back-up important data on XP, format and install Windows 7 so that you get a clean system instead of a crappy upgrade. If I remember well that the 95-&gt;98 upgrade was kind of crappy.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">he reasons for less efficient Os'es are obvious. By making there new Operating systems slower people must purchase new computers to make them work, this further fuels the industry. A one hand washes the other kinda thing.</div><br />People are forced to upgrade because new hardware isn't supported by old software : You can't use wifi, webcams and stuff with Windows 2000, and you can't even use USB stuff with Windows 98 without some MAJOR trouble. XP, on the other side, is supposed to be up-to date until 2014, which is in 5 years, at which point my new PC will probably get an old piece of crap  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_cry.gif" alt=":cry:" title="Crying or Very sad" /> <br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> <br /><br />I'm testing it a little bit here and there. I still don't see the point for all the new fluff they added. I was able to restore the task bar to work like it was before, put back the quick launch but the only think I cannot put back is the %%$#% start menu. I don't like it.</div><br />I couldn't agree more. It's really COMPLETELY messed up. The config panel is only a bit messed up but workable.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">1GB of RAM for an OS is ridiculous. It doesn't matter if you have 8GB, it's still ridiculous, specially considering that XP ran pretty well with 128MB.</div>
<br />True, but again can you code a better OS ? If you can I'd take it :p</div>

					
