				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Sep 19, 2004 9:28 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 1051<br /><b>Location:</b> Mountain View, CA, USA
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Anders_A wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I find it more ridiculous to leave RAM unused. It's great that windows and other operating systems finally use the RAM you have to speed things up.<br /><br />What's your reasoning behind leaving RAM unused until programs request it instead of using it and releasing it when programs request it?</div>
<br />
<br />There's two reasons this mentality is silly for most things
<br />
<br />1) The OS allocating contiguous amounts of memory is not a "painful" process -- meaning the whole procedure is actually quite fast.  The same goes for freeing memory back to the OS.  The concept "use only what you need" applies here.  It only becomes a slow procedure as memory becomes more and more segmented (that is to say, a varied amount of allocations of various sizes are scattered all over, rather than being linear).
<br />
<br />2) The OS has no intrinsic knowledge of how much memory an application is going to require down the road/over time.  I suppose it could keep an average of this somehow, but would you not agree keeping track of that would probably waste more system resources in general.
<br />
<br />#2 is solvable -- that is to say, there *are* applications out there which do preallocate large amounts of memory.  The amount allocated is almost always user-adjustable, but the default is often based off of how much free memory is available at the time (e.g. free/4, or some other similar formula).
<br />
<br />Depending on what the overall application requires, sacrificing memory for speed can in fact be worth it.  When is it worth it?  That's for the programmer to decide.  There's a multitude of situations where it's justified, but even more where it's not.
<br />
<br />Two "real world" applications that I know which behave this way are: Adobe Photoshop and Sun Java (both the JRE, and the JVM as a whole).  Photoshop's well-justified, while (IMHO) Java generally isn't.
<br />
<br />There's another real world scenario where preallocation is easily worth it: low-latency scenarios.  I happen to <a href="http://www.tellme.com/" class="postlink">work at such a place</a> -- we basically "bridge the gap" between the telephone and computers.  Fast voice recognition + parsing what the user said + giving them immediate feedback is of the utmost importance -- e.g. 0.3 seconds is considered a very long time.  So for this type of scenario, preallocation is absolutely mandatory.  Machines with 4-16GB of RAM are incredibly common, and daemons preallocate on startup for a very good reason (think: grammar syntax, audio content, parsers, and general voice analysis (audio is big!)).
<br />
<br />In general I'm a minimalist myself, within reason.  So I'm very much against the concept of a "macrocosmic OS" (e.g. Super Size Everything, no concept of free memory, etc.).  If you know you're going to need 60MB of memory, fine, allocate it.  If you don't know how much you're going to need, but it's significantly smaller, allocate it dynamically and free it when done.
<br />
<br />This whole thing becomes even more complex when you consider threaded environments, where termination of a thread releases all memory the thread had allocated back to the OS.  Given that SMP (think: multi-core) is common today, overall higher amounts of memory usage is acceptable.  By that I mean, the OS "chewing up" 700MB of RAM when you have 4GB really isn't that bad... unless, of course, you REALLY COULD use that extra memory for something (see above, re: Photoshop).
<br />
<br />That remind me -- there is one utility from SysInternals (now Microsoft) for Windows which is absolutely awesome.  It's called <a href="http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/dd535533.aspx" class="postlink">VMMap</a>.  Check it out -- but it's important you understand what it is you're looking at!  I run into this situation all the time in the UNIX world.  "When I run top, why is this one process eating up 800MB of RAM?"  "Actually, the 800MB is under SIZE, not RSS/RES, which means 800MB is being used and shared across multiple applications/programs (text/data/stack segments).  800MB of RSS/RES (resident) would indicate a much bigger problem, and likely indicates a memory leak."  "Ohh... nevermind then."
<br />
<br />Windows does things similarly in concept, but the implementation/style of their VM is *very* different.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

