						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It frustrates me that we simply can't have an operating system that "flies"</div><br />You may not have seen the work that the Moblin project did on the Linux boot process. There are <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s7NxCM8ryF8" class="postlink">literally five seconds</a> from the end of POST to a desktop and an idle disk. <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">When new/faster hardware is released, they make an OS that will perform in them like the old OS performed in the old machine. WTF? It's like they are saying "Yeah, Operating systems are this slow, and they are supposed to be like this on current machines, deal with it". I wish they'd run "super fast", not "just fine".</div><br />Features other than performance sell more than performance. That's why we have <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wirth%27s_law" class="postlink">Wirth's law</a>.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Maybe they are relying on fast hardware too much. I don't know if it's just laziness or something, like they are encapsulating stuff many levels deep instead of actually coding something more efficient.</div><br />Laziness allows features to get implemented more quickly. Features allow copies to get sold to users.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">1GB of RAM for an OS is ridiculous. It doesn't matter if you have 8GB, it's still ridiculous, specially considering that XP ran pretty well with 128MB.</div><br />Would you want to use an operating system with the capabilities of Windows 3.1?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Soon you'll not be able to do many tasks you could before. I heard Microsoft is using some sort of Media protection that will prevent you from running anything (music, videos) that's not digitally signed (i.e. not pirate)</div><br />Signed by whom? How will Start &gt; Programs &gt; Accessories &gt; Entertainment &gt; Sound Recorder function in such an environment?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'm tired of using pirate software</div><br />Like 99 percent of the ROMs on most people's emulators?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And since I think the original stuff is hardly worth what they are charging (Vista I won't take even if they pay me, haven't tried 7 yet), I'll end up going the free software route.</div><br />If you want to develop for Xbox 360's app store, you need Windows in order to run XNA Game Studio.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">because if I put back the style to the classic one... What would I not be using winxp instead then?</div><br />Windows 7 supports a newer version of DirectX, and it will continue to get security patches even after XP support is discontinued.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I can't tell you exactly which version it is because the "System" icon that used to always be on the topleft of the desktop since 95 isn't here, and I can't check it's properties.</div><br />There are other ways to get to My Computer even if it's hidden from your desktop. Here are a couple from XP:<br />Start &gt; Control Panel &gt; System<br />Start &gt; My Computer &gt; Properties<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">You can't use wifi, webcams and stuff with Windows 2000</div><br />WLAN is just LAN, and webcam is just video capture. If a given peripheral manufacturer chose not to provide a Windows 2000-compatible driver back in 2002-2003 or whenever you bought the hardware, there were other manufacturers that did.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">but again can you code a better OS ? If you can I'd take it :p</div><br />Linux scales beautifully. It comes in both lightweight distros (e.g. Xubuntu, Puppy) and heavyweight distros (e.g. Ubuntu Desktop). Microsoft made a lightweight XP (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Fundamentals_for_Legacy_PCs" class="postlink">Windows Fundamentals for Legacy PCs</a>) to replace Windows 98 on PCs of its Software Assurance customers, but it decided against selling copies to the public for some odd reason.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Anders_A wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I find it more ridiculous to leave RAM unused.</div><br />There are a few problems with this statement:<br /><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>As kyuusaku pointed out, If a whole stick of RAM is unused, the hardware should ideally be able to power it down. </li><li>Latency, as koitsu pointed out. Sure, an operating system can use RAM for caching, but when I want to use the RAM for something else, it had better repurpose that RAM pretty damn quick without a lot of thrashing. That's why I have swappiness turned down to 10% on my Ubuntu laptop, that and the fact that reads are much faster than writes on a cheap SSD. </li><li>Assuming a large cache makes it too easy for the operating system's developers not to optimize for low-RAM machines. That might be commercially OK if your portables run a completely different codebase from your desktops (e.g. Windows Mobile vs. Windows). </li></ol><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">2) The OS has no intrinsic knowledge of how much memory an application is going to require down the road/over time.</div>
<br />Classic Mac OS supported "high water marks" for applications beyond which malloc() would fail. Each executable would have its high water mark in its properties box, which the user could edit.</div>

